<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-409-610  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 409 610.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Executive  Spring 1990 v3 n2 p42(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Information as a competitive weapon.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fleck, Robert A. Jr.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many companies successfully use information systems as strategic,competitive weapons to lower costs, add value to their products,and provide differentiated services.andP;  Internally, companies haveused strategic data advantageously to reduce employee travelexpenses, develop more effective marketing strategies, and curtailemployee pilferage.andP;  Externally, companies have used strategicdata to differentiate themselves from their competition.andP;  Examplesof this include an expert system developed by American Express tofacilitate credit card authorization, a centralized informationsystem developed by Otis Elevator Corp to track elevatorservicing, and a computerized order entry system developed byAmerican Hospital Supply Corp. Information technology nowpermeates the value chain at every point, but it is important toremember that even the strongest strategic systems couldeventually become 'a cost of doing business' as the competitioncatches up.andP;  By examining successful strategic systems, we learnthat champions are needed to stand behind them, computers are nota substitute for planning and management, and informationtechnology is more than just computers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CompetitionInformation Resources ManagementInformation SystemsMarketing StrategyCase StudyCost ReductionStrategic Planning.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Information pyramid. (chart)Information intensity and content. (chart)Strategic importance of information systems. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>